messages.content: Data is beautiful and here are some results

Proof of Weights: Validators generate a zk-proof to show they have actually run the scoring function of a subnet to achieve the weights submitted to chain. The proofs are unique to the validator, even if the end score is exactly the same, so a validator cannot copy another's generated proof. Yuma already ensures the miners are being scored fairly, so it's not to ensure the validator has correctly run the code, but just prove it was run at all.

This is actually where the name Omron comes from. The Omron Rings, or EURion constellation is a pattern of symbols incorporated into a number of secure documents such as banknotes and paper checks, designed to prevent the direct counterfeiting using photocopiers or imaging software. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EURion_constellation

And then how we see this implemented at the protocol level: SN owners decide to enable Proof of Weights as a hyperparameter. When enabled, validators who do not submit proof of weights take a hit to Vtrust and therefore dividends.

Check our progress on Proof of Weights here: https://github.com/inference-labs-inc/omron-subnet/pull/4

How would the chain verify that the proof is legit?

Each subnet converts their scoring function into a computational graph which is then converted into a zk-circuit.

-> https://github.com/inference-labs-inc/omron-subnet/pull/4/files#diff-cb9903b90e4f206c7c73ba6d45f61bd450fac7a1f2aff0d229f246c5a1f80879R46

From there, a public verification key is produced. This would be committed by the subnet owner to be used on chain and updated as the scoring function evolves over time. When validators run the scoring function, they have [ inputs ] -> reward function -> [weights] + zk proof.

As validators submit weights, they must also commit a proof to show the scoring function was run. This is the same process we do for miners, where the validators verify miners have run a model correctly without needing to rerun it themselves. The chain would not need to rerun the scoring function but rather just verify the proof is correct.

Great question and insightful observation! Indeed, there is a direct relationship between a specific model, the zk proving system, and the size of the proof. When we talk about reducing proof sizes, we're referring to a holistic approach within this subnet. The network incentivizes miners to optimize across the entire stack—this includes enhancements at the hardware level, within MLops, the environment, and the proving systems, alongside more optimized and succinct models. As a result, we anticipate that proof sizes will naturally decrease over time as mining becomes increasingly competitive, leading to continuous improvements that benefit the whole system.

Smaller proofs are generally considered better because they are cheaper to store, both on & off-chain. The cost of doing on-chain verification is a function of gas + call data. As eventually inference output is verified / used on-chain, it makes sense to incentivize this early on. As for miners + proof size, in our next release miners will be tasked with distilling a larger model into a smaller one while keeping loss minimized. This is a multivariate problem, so compute time + model loss + proof size will all be a factor in incentive.
